<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910115-0040</DOCNO><DOCID>910115-0040.</DOCID><HL>   Business Brief -- Great Country Bank:   Wider Second-Quarter Loss   Of $12.5 Million Is Posted</HL><DATE>01/15/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), NO PAGE CITATION</SO><CO>   GCBK</CO><IN>EASTERN U.S. BANKS (BAE)BANKS (BNK)EARNINGS (ERN)</IN><LP>   Great Country Bank, Ansonia, Conn., hit by persistentdeclines in the regional real estate market, reported a muchwider loss in its fiscal second quarter as it increased itsloan-loss provision.   The company's net loss for the second quarter ended Nov.30 increased sharply to $12.5 million, or $5.70 a share, from$816,000, or 37 cents a share, in the year-earlier period.The bank took a $10.1 million loan-loss provision, comparedwith a $1.3 million provision in the year-earlier quarter.</LP><TEXT>   Frederick J. Quinn, president of Great Country, blamedConnecticut's real estate market and the general economy. Hesaid the company has taken steps to improve productivity,including a 21% reduction in personnel over the past year.   For the six months, Great Country reported a wider loss of$13.4 million, or $6.12 a share, compared with a loss of $4.8million, or $2.20 a share, a year earlier. Loan-lossprovisions increased to $11.3 million from $8.5 million.   In national over-the-counter trading yesterday, GreatCountry Bank shares fell 75 cents to close at $1.75.</TEXT></DOC>